Artists For Charity, which has served HIV positive orphans for more than a decade in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, has broadened its reach with the establishment of a Community Center to meet the needs of HIV positive children living with relatives or foster families in one of the poorest districts in Addis Ababa. The Community Center Project is currently serving twenty (20) children and their caregivers with monthly living stipends, school support, health services, mentoring and counseling. The goal is to increase  the number of children and families served, and to increase the services provided to these beneficiaries.  To this end, AFC has leased a building in Kolfe that is easily accessible to these families and has plenty of space for potential programs and services. But to make it a real, functioning community center we need furnishings, equipment, books, games and supplies.Many of the HIV positive children who are and who will be served by the Community Center did not have adequate access to school or healthcare before AFC, and found themselves coping with the challenges of living with HIV without support. With AFC’s support, they do go to school, they receive tutoring, counseling and mentoring; and they have a safe place to go to strengthen their minds and bodies, a place to safely spend time among peers and helping adults - a place to be kids.  AFC is taking on a project that it cannot complete without help. We need supporters who believe in the power of love, education, mentoring and structured play to help us complete this mission.  What we have:
A facility in a safe, accessible compound in Kolfe, one of the poorest districts in Addis Ababa;
A small but dedicated staff and a diverse team of twenty (20) volunteers;
An influential local advisory board to help identify needs and the best way to respond; 
Many orphaned and vulnerable children with enormous potential. 
What we need:$4,000 to provide furnishings, equipment, books, games, toys and supplies.Why AFC?Since its beginnings, AFC’s programs and services have been overwhelmingly successful. Every child has overcome the threat of HIV and every child who has aged out of the orphanage has completed school – no mean feat in Ethiopia - and a significant number have gone on to university. Others have completed vocational training programs or started businesses and become self-supporting, successful adults. The playground completed at Yekatit hospital last year has been widely celebrated and held up as a model for other hospitals and communities in a city of more than four million people and no other accessible hospital playgrounds.  Artists For Charityis a 501(c) (3) non-profit organization, and all donations towards this project are tax-deductible. Learn more about AFC and ways you can become involved by visiting us at: www.artistsforcharity.org! Help by sharing!No matter how much you are able to give to our campaign, you can also support this project by spreading the word!  Please share this link with friends, family and colleagues.
